Note:
==============================================================================
hsl - HSL and HSV Cylindrical Color Models
==============================================================================

ColorHsl and ColorHsv are cylindrical reformulations of RGB that make hue,
saturation, and lightness / value directly addressable. Both encode hue
as an angular position in degrees [0, 360); the saturation, lightness,
and value components live in the unit interval [0, 1].

The RGB <-> HSL and RGB <-> HSV conversions follow the formulae of Smith
(SIGGRAPH 1978) and the W3C CSS Color Module Level 4 reference, with hue
continuity verified at the six 60-degree sextant boundaries. Round-trip
identity is preserved to machine precision when inputs lie strictly in
the open unit cube.

This module operates on ColorRgb values from rgb.runa for the public API.
Saturation and lightness manipulators (hsl_lighten, hsl_saturate, ...) are
expressed as in-place HSL transforms returning new HSL values; callers
that want to round-trip through sRGB must use hsl_to_rgb after applying
the transform.

References:
  - A. R. Smith, "Color Gamut Transform Pairs", SIGGRAPH 1978
  - W3C CSS Color Module Level 4, Section "HSL Colors"
==============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
RGB at this module's public boundary is represented as four Float
channels (r, g, b, a) so callers can pass values produced by any sRGB
source without first wrapping them in a struct from rgb.runa. RGB
outputs are written into a caller-supplied 32-byte buffer at the
canonical offsets 0/8/16/24. Internal helpers manipulate ColorHsl and
ColorHsv structs and exchange them with sibling colour modules via
qualified imports.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRUCT TYPE DEFINITIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "ColorHsl":
    h as Float
    s as Float
    l as Float
    a as Float
End Type

Type called "ColorHsv":
    h as Float
    s as Float
    v as Float
    a as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LOCAL HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "clamp01" takes v as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Saturate to [0, 1].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two compares.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two ucomisd + two cmovs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If v is less than 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    If v is greater than 1.0:
        Return 1.0
    End If
    Return v
End Process

Process called "normalize_hue" takes h as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Wrap hue to [0, 360). Bounded loop terminates in O(|h|/360) iterations
    capped at 4096 for safety.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Add or subtract 360 until h lies in canonical range.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Typically 0 or 1 iterations.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure, bounded loop.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let result be h
    Let guard be 0
    While guard is less than 4096:
        If result is greater than or equal to 360.0:
            Set result to result minus 360.0
            Set guard to guard plus 1
        Otherwise:
            If result is less than 0.0:
                Set result to result plus 360.0
                Set guard to guard plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return result
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Process called "max3" takes a as Float, b as Float, c as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Three-way maximum.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two sequential compares.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let m be a
    If b is greater than m:
        Set m to b
    End If
    If c is greater than m:
        Set m to c
    End If
    Return m
End Process

Process called "min3" takes a as Float, b as Float, c as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Three-way minimum.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two sequential compares.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let m be a
    If b is less than m:
        Set m to b
    End If
    If c is less than m:
        Set m to c
    End If
    Return m
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTORS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "hsl_create" takes h as Float, s as Float, l as Float, a as Float returns ColorHsl:
    @Reasoning
    Construct an HSL color with hue normalised and saturation, lightness,
    alpha clamped to [0, 1].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct normalisation per component.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One bounded loop plus three clamps.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorHsl
    Set out.h to normalize_hue(h)
    Set out.s to clamp01(s)
    Set out.l to clamp01(l)
    Set out.a to clamp01(a)
    Return out
End Process

Process called "hsv_create" takes h as Float, s as Float, v as Float, a as Float returns ColorHsv:
    @Reasoning
    Construct an HSV color.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Hue normalisation and unit-interval clamps.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same cost as hsl_create.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorHsv
    Set out.h to normalize_hue(h)
    Set out.s to clamp01(s)
    Set out.v to clamp01(v)
    Set out.a to clamp01(a)
    Return out
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RGB <-> HSL CONVERSIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "hsl_from_rgb" takes r as Float, g as Float, b as Float, a as Float returns ColorHsl:
    @Reasoning
    Convert a sRGB ColorRgb (passed as four Float channels) to HSL using
    the Smith / CSS-COLOR-4 formula. Computes lightness as (max + min)/2,
    saturation as delta/(1 - |2L - 1|), and hue from the dominant channel
    sextant.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Branchless after the max / min identification; sextant dispatch via
    three explicit compares.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~25 FLOPs in the common case.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let max_v be max3(r, g, b)
    Let min_v be min3(r, g, b)
    Let delta be max_v minus min_v
    Let l_val be (max_v plus min_v) divided by 2.0
    Let s_val be 0.0
    Let h_val be 0.0
    If delta is greater than 0.0:
        Let denom be 1.0 minus Arith.absf((2.0 multiplied by l_val) minus 1.0)
        If denom is greater than 0.0:
            Set s_val to delta divided by denom
        End If
        If r is greater than or equal to max_v:
            If r is equal to max_v:
                Set h_val to ((g minus b) divided by delta) modulo by 6.0
            Otherwise:
                If g is equal to max_v:
                    Set h_val to ((b minus r) divided by delta) plus 2.0
                Otherwise:
                    Set h_val to ((r minus g) divided by delta) plus 4.0
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If g is greater than or equal to b:
                Set h_val to ((b minus r) divided by delta) plus 2.0
            Otherwise:
                Set h_val to ((r minus g) divided by delta) plus 4.0
            End If
        End If
        Set h_val to h_val multiplied by 60.0
        Set h_val to normalize_hue(h_val)
    End If
    Let out be a value of type ColorHsl
    Set out.h to h_val
    Set out.s to clamp01(s_val)
    Set out.l to clamp01(l_val)
    Set out.a to a
    Return out
End Process

Process called "hue_to_rgb_component" takes p as Float, q as Float, t_in as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Internal helper for hsl_to_rgb implementing the per-channel sextant
    interpolation. Inputs p, q are derived from L and S; t selects the
    channel via offsets {+1/3, 0, -1/3}.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Six-sextant piecewise linear evaluator.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, no loops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let t be t_in
    If t is less than 0.0:
        Set t to t plus 1.0
    End If
    If t is greater than 1.0:
        Set t to t minus 1.0
    End If
    If t is less than (1.0 divided by 6.0):
        Return p plus ((q minus p) multiplied by (6.0 multiplied by t))
    End If
    If t is less than 0.5:
        Return q
    End If
    If t is less than (2.0 divided by 3.0):
        Return p plus ((q minus p) multiplied by (((2.0 divided by 3.0) minus t) multiplied by 6.0))
    End If
    Return p
End Process

Process called "hsl_to_rgb" takes c as ColorHsl, out_rgb as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Convert an HSL triple into a sRGB color (four Float channels) and
    write them into the caller-supplied 32-byte buffer at offsets
    0 (r) / 8 (g) / 16 (b) / 24 (a). When saturation is zero the result
    is achromatic at the given lightness.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    p = 2L - q, q = L*(1+S) when L<0.5, q = L+S - L*S otherwise. Channel
    floats are stored via the float_to_bits helper.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~ 30 FLOPs per call plus four 8-byte stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller guarantees out_rgb has at least 32 writable bytes.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let h_norm be c.h divided by 360.0
    If c.s is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Let _r be store_float_at(out_rgb, 0, c.l)
        Let _g be store_float_at(out_rgb, 8, c.l)
        Let _b be store_float_at(out_rgb, 16, c.l)
        Let _a be store_float_at(out_rgb, 24, c.a)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let q_val be 0.0
    If c.l is less than 0.5:
        Set q_val to c.l multiplied by (1.0 plus c.s)
    Otherwise:
        Set q_val to (c.l plus c.s) minus (c.l multiplied by c.s)
    End If
    Let p_val be (2.0 multiplied by c.l) minus q_val
    Let r_v be hue_to_rgb_component(p_val, q_val, h_norm plus (1.0 divided by 3.0))
    Let g_v be hue_to_rgb_component(p_val, q_val, h_norm)
    Let b_v be hue_to_rgb_component(p_val, q_val, h_norm minus (1.0 divided by 3.0))
    Let _wr be store_float_at(out_rgb, 0, clamp01(r_v))
    Let _wg be store_float_at(out_rgb, 8, clamp01(g_v))
    Let _wb be store_float_at(out_rgb, 16, clamp01(b_v))
    Let _wa be store_float_at(out_rgb, 24, clamp01(c.a))
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RGB <-> HSV CONVERSIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "hsv_from_rgb" takes r as Float, g as Float, b as Float, a as Float returns ColorHsv:
    @Reasoning
    Convert a sRGB color (four Float channels) to HSV. Value is the max
    channel, saturation is delta / max, hue is the dominant-channel
    sextant.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same dispatch shape as hsl_from_rgb but with V = max and
    S = delta / max.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~ 20 FLOPs per call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let max_v be max3(r, g, b)
    Let min_v be min3(r, g, b)
    Let delta be max_v minus min_v
    Let v_val be max_v
    Let s_val be 0.0
    Let h_val be 0.0
    If max_v is greater than 0.0:
        Set s_val to delta divided by max_v
    End If
    If delta is greater than 0.0:
        If r is equal to max_v:
            Set h_val to ((g minus b) divided by delta) modulo by 6.0
        Otherwise:
            If g is equal to max_v:
                Set h_val to ((b minus r) divided by delta) plus 2.0
            Otherwise:
                Set h_val to ((r minus g) divided by delta) plus 4.0
            End If
        End If
        Set h_val to h_val multiplied by 60.0
        Set h_val to normalize_hue(h_val)
    End If
    Let out be a value of type ColorHsv
    Set out.h to h_val
    Set out.s to clamp01(s_val)
    Set out.v to clamp01(v_val)
    Set out.a to a
    Return out
End Process

Process called "hsv_to_rgb" takes c as ColorHsv, out_rgb as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Convert HSV to sRGB ColorRgb using the six-sextant dispatch defined
    by Smith. The sextant index i = floor(h / 60) selects which two
    channels carry the chroma.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Chroma = V * S, X = chroma * (1 - |((h/60) mod 2) - 1|), m = V - chroma.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two FP truncations, six compares, ~12 FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let h_norm be c.h
    If h_norm is greater than or equal to 360.0:
        Set h_norm to h_norm minus 360.0
    End If
    If h_norm is less than 0.0:
        Set h_norm to h_norm plus 360.0
    End If
    Let chroma be c.v multiplied by c.s
    Let h_prime be h_norm divided by 60.0
    Let two_mod be h_prime modulo by 2.0
    Let xx be chroma multiplied by (1.0 minus Arith.absf(two_mod minus 1.0))
    Let r1 be 0.0
    Let g1 be 0.0
    Let b1 be 0.0
    If h_prime is less than 1.0:
        Set r1 to chroma
        Set g1 to xx
        Set b1 to 0.0
    Otherwise:
        If h_prime is less than 2.0:
            Set r1 to xx
            Set g1 to chroma
            Set b1 to 0.0
        Otherwise:
            If h_prime is less than 3.0:
                Set r1 to 0.0
                Set g1 to chroma
                Set b1 to xx
            Otherwise:
                If h_prime is less than 4.0:
                    Set r1 to 0.0
                    Set g1 to xx
                    Set b1 to chroma
                Otherwise:
                    If h_prime is less than 5.0:
                        Set r1 to xx
                        Set g1 to 0.0
                        Set b1 to chroma
                    Otherwise:
                        Set r1 to chroma
                        Set g1 to 0.0
                        Set b1 to xx
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Let m_val be c.v minus chroma
    Let _wr be store_float_at(out_rgb, 0, clamp01(r1 plus m_val))
    Let _wg be store_float_at(out_rgb, 8, clamp01(g1 plus m_val))
    Let _wb be store_float_at(out_rgb, 16, clamp01(b1 plus m_val))
    Let _wa be store_float_at(out_rgb, 24, clamp01(c.a))
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HSL MANIPULATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "hsl_lighten" takes c as ColorHsl, amount as Float returns ColorHsl:
    @Reasoning
    Increase lightness by an additive amount, clamped into [0, 1].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    L' = clamp(L + amount).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single add + clamp.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorHsl
    Set out.h to c.h
    Set out.s to c.s
    Set out.l to clamp01(c.l plus amount)
    Set out.a to c.a
    Return out
End Process

Process called "hsl_darken" takes c as ColorHsl, amount as Float returns ColorHsl:
    @Reasoning
    Decrease lightness by an additive amount.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    L' = clamp(L - amount).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single subtract + clamp.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorHsl
    Set out.h to c.h
    Set out.s to c.s
    Set out.l to clamp01(c.l minus amount)
    Set out.a to c.a
    Return out
End Process

Process called "hsl_saturate" takes c as ColorHsl, amount as Float returns ColorHsl:
    @Reasoning
    Increase saturation by an additive amount.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    S' = clamp(S + amount).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single add + clamp.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorHsl
    Set out.h to c.h
    Set out.s to clamp01(c.s plus amount)
    Set out.l to c.l
    Set out.a to c.a
    Return out
End Process

Process called "hsl_desaturate" takes c as ColorHsl, amount as Float returns ColorHsl:
    @Reasoning
    Decrease saturation by an additive amount.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    S' = clamp(S - amount).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single subtract + clamp.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorHsl
    Set out.h to c.h
    Set out.s to clamp01(c.s minus amount)
    Set out.l to c.l
    Set out.a to c.a
    Return out
End Process

Process called "hsl_rotate_hue" takes c as ColorHsl, degrees as Float returns ColorHsl:
    @Reasoning
    Rotate the hue angle by a signed number of degrees.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    h' = normalize_hue(h + degrees).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single add + bounded modulus loop.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorHsl
    Set out.h to normalize_hue(c.h plus degrees)
    Set out.s to c.s
    Set out.l to c.l
    Set out.a to c.a
    Return out
End Process

