Note: ============================================================================
Note: BIT-CAST HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "float_to_bits" takes x as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Bit-cast Float64 to its 64-bit integer pattern, used to feed
    memory_set_int64 when writing channel buffers.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Inline assembly performs a register-to-register move via the
    Float-occupying stack slot.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single mov.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        mov rax, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        mov qword ptr [rbp-16], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "store_float_at" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Bit-cast a Float64 to its 64-bit pattern and store at ptr+offset.
    Used for writing colour channels into caller-supplied buffers.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    float_to_bits then memory_set_int64.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two movs + one store.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns ptr.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let bits be float_to_bits(value)
    Let _w be Memory.memory_set_int64(ptr, offset, bits)
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "bits_to_float" takes b as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Bit-cast a 64-bit integer back to Float64. Inverse of float_to_bits.
    Used to recover Float channels written to a buffer by hsl_to_rgb /
    hsv_to_rgb before re-feeding them through the inverse RGB->HSL/HSV
    converters.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Inline assembly moves the integer-occupying stack slot through the
    Float-occupying slot.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single mov.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let result be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        mov rax, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        mov qword ptr [rbp-16], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DIRECT HSV <-> HSL CONVERSIONS (Smith 1978 round-trip via sRGB)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "hsv_to_hsl" takes c as ColorHsv returns ColorHsl:
    @Reasoning
    Convert an HSV triple to its HSL equivalent. HSV and HSL share the
    hue exactly but assign saturation and the third axis (value /
    lightness) via different geometries: HSV.value = max(r, g, b),
    HSL.lightness = (max + min)/2. Routing through the canonical sRGB
    triple guarantees that the recovered HSL describes the same point
    in the unit RGB cube as the input HSV did.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocate a 32-byte scratch buffer on the owned heap, call hsv_to_rgb
    into it, recover the (r, g, b, a) channels via bits_to_float, then
    invoke hsl_from_rgb on the recovered channels. Buffer is released
    before return. On allocation failure returns an HSL preserving the
    HSV hue with zeroed s / l.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~30 FLOPs for the forward + reverse conversion, plus one 32-byte
    alloc and one free.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Allocates and frees its own scratch deterministically.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let scratch be Layout.allocate(32)
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Let fallback be a value of type ColorHsl
        Set fallback.h to c.h
        Set fallback.s to 0.0
        Set fallback.l to 0.0
        Set fallback.a to c.a
        Return fallback
    End If
    Let _w be hsv_to_rgb(c, scratch)
    Let r_val be bits_to_float(Memory.memory_get_int64(scratch, 0))
    Let g_val be bits_to_float(Memory.memory_get_int64(scratch, 8))
    Let b_val be bits_to_float(Memory.memory_get_int64(scratch, 16))
    Let a_val be bits_to_float(Memory.memory_get_int64(scratch, 24))
    Let _d be Layout.deallocate(scratch)
    Return hsl_from_rgb(r_val, g_val, b_val, a_val)
End Process

Process called "hsl_to_hsv" takes c as ColorHsl returns ColorHsv:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of hsv_to_hsl. Routes through sRGB to recover the canonical
    HSV triple matching the input HSL point in the unit RGB cube.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocate a 32-byte scratch on the owned heap, call hsl_to_rgb into
    it, recover the (r, g, b, a) channels via bits_to_float, then invoke
    hsv_from_rgb. Buffer is released before return. On allocation
    failure returns an HSV preserving the HSL hue with zeroed s / v.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~30 FLOPs for the forward + reverse conversion, plus one 32-byte
    alloc and one free.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Allocates and frees its own scratch deterministically.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let scratch be Layout.allocate(32)
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Let fallback be a value of type ColorHsv
        Set fallback.h to c.h
        Set fallback.s to 0.0
        Set fallback.v to 0.0
        Set fallback.a to c.a
        Return fallback
    End If
    Let _w be hsl_to_rgb(c, scratch)
    Let r_val be bits_to_float(Memory.memory_get_int64(scratch, 0))
    Let g_val be bits_to_float(Memory.memory_get_int64(scratch, 8))
    Let b_val be bits_to_float(Memory.memory_get_int64(scratch, 16))
    Let a_val be bits_to_float(Memory.memory_get_int64(scratch, 24))
    Let _d be Layout.deallocate(scratch)
    Return hsv_from_rgb(r_val, g_val, b_val, a_val)
End Process
